1
00:00:03,040 --> 00:00:06,120
Mom, I think the hamster peed.
-Shai, come on, do me a favor,

2
00:00:06,200 --> 00:00:08,360
it's gonna soak into the upholstery,
it's gonna smell bad in here.

3
00:00:08,440 --> 00:00:11,640
Sit down, wait, don’t be hysterical.
It’s just a couple of drops, his pee.

4
00:00:11,720 --> 00:00:13,680
He also poops on his bedding.
-Do me a favor,

5
00:00:13,840 --> 00:00:16,160
when it comes to hamsters, you have no say at all.

6
00:00:16,239 --> 00:00:18,080
Believe me, the moment you brought him home,
I should’ve kicked

7
00:00:18,160 --> 00:00:20,440
all three of you out of the house.
-All three of us?

8
00:00:20,520 --> 00:00:22,880
Yeah. You, the hamster, and the bedding.
-Okay, what do you want me to do?

9
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:26,360
The girl wanted a hamster.
-Great, and if the girl wants a mom,

10
00:00:26,440 --> 00:00:27,480
are you gonna buy her one too?
-What mom?

11
00:00:27,560 --> 00:00:30,600
A mom. The girl gets a pet mom. So buy her one.

12
00:00:30,800 --> 00:00:32,080
Can I get a mom?
-Here, please.

13
00:00:32,159 --> 00:00:33,360
Sss... Amen.

14
00:00:33,520 --> 00:00:36,000
Don’t worry, babe, on Sunday Dad will buy you a mom

15
00:00:36,120 --> 00:00:39,080
but on Sunday afternoon because on Sunday
morning he’s going to the Interior Ministry

16
00:00:39,160 --> 00:00:40,760
to change his name to Dr. Dolittle.

17
00:00:47,120 --> 00:00:49,600
Look at me, look at me and...

18
00:01:04,200 --> 00:01:05,720
Come on, Dad, what, are you watching horse riding?

19
00:01:05,800 --> 00:01:07,840
What do you want? What... it’s a sport.

20
00:01:07,920 --> 00:01:10,560
It’s the only place where someone
walks around all day with their legs spread

21
00:01:10,640 --> 00:01:12,240
and a whip in hand and it’s not weird.

22
00:01:12,840 --> 00:01:15,360
You just ruined all the fun for me.
-What fun is that?

23
00:01:15,440 --> 00:01:16,360
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom.

24
00:01:16,440 --> 00:01:17,560
Shabbat Shalom.

25
00:01:18,760 --> 00:01:20,920
What’s that smell?
-I told you it stinks,

26
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:22,000
I’m not the only one saying it.

27
00:01:22,080 --> 00:01:24,720
What is it? What is it? What did you bring? Not here, not here.

28
00:01:24,880 --> 00:01:26,680
Over there, over there, put it there.

29
00:01:26,760 --> 00:01:29,320
The girls wanted a pet so...
-Yeah, Shai bought them a hamster.

30
00:01:29,440 --> 00:01:31,880
Really, put Justin Bieber
on the balcony! Don’t take him out of there.

31
00:01:31,960 --> 00:01:34,480
Bieber is a doll, right?
-Yeah, that’s the name the girls gave

32
00:01:34,600 --> 00:01:37,520
to the hamster Shai brought them.
As for me, I’m taking that hamster

33
00:01:37,600 --> 00:01:40,040
and giving him a wireless bungee jump off the balcony.
-What, that’s unnecessary.

34
00:01:40,120 --> 00:01:44,160
Why do you need a hamster?
It only brings diseases.

35
00:01:44,240 --> 00:01:47,080
Why “only diseases”?
-Right, Shai is right. Why only diseases?

36
00:01:47,160 --> 00:01:49,200
It’s also poop, also pee, also stink, also dirt,

37
00:01:49,360 --> 00:01:52,840
the diseases are the fun part of the whole thing.
I’m going to eat.

38
00:01:55,160 --> 00:01:57,560
I have a feeling that if it were technically possible for her,
she’d attach you

39
00:01:57,640 --> 00:01:59,720
to that wireless bungee jump along with Justin Bieber.

40
00:02:00,640 --> 00:02:03,720
It’s a bit discouraging because all the efforts
I make to not annoy her

41
00:02:04,320 --> 00:02:06,440
go to waste.
-Hot blood,

42
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:10,680
and every time you burn her
thermostat again. You get it?

43
00:02:10,759 --> 00:02:13,960
Why are you in a fighting mood today?
-Why? Because Shai bought a hamster for the girls.

44
00:02:14,680 --> 00:02:16,600
One that looks like a rat and smells like a person.

45
00:02:17,360 --> 00:02:19,680
A hamster?
-Yeah, yeah. It’s not the hamster itself,

46
00:02:20,080 --> 00:02:22,280
it annoys me that Shai decides on his own.

47
00:02:22,360 --> 00:02:26,640
Like he lives on some island of his own.
-Babe, he’s a man, that’s how men are.

48
00:02:27,200 --> 00:02:29,400
He wanted to cheer the girls up a bit. What’s wrong with that?

49
00:02:29,520 --> 00:02:31,880
Okay, okay, but he should call
before he does something silly,

50
00:02:32,040 --> 00:02:35,160
just ask a little question: “Do you mind
having a rodent at home?”

51
00:02:35,280 --> 00:02:37,760
It’s obvious I’d say no, but come on, he should ask.

52
00:02:37,840 --> 00:02:39,960
So why did you agree to bring him home?
-The hamster?

53
00:02:40,080 --> 00:02:41,280
Shai.
-Because the girls cried.

54
00:02:41,360 --> 00:02:42,520
They wouldn’t let him stay outside.

55
00:02:42,600 --> 00:02:44,040
Who, the hamster?
-Shai.

56
00:02:44,760 --> 00:02:47,520
Now how do I get rid of him
without hurting her or the girls?

57
00:02:47,640 --> 00:02:49,680
There are much easier questions than this
that I can’t solve.

58
00:02:49,760 --> 00:02:52,000
You started with the complicated one.
-Come on, enough with the nonsense.

59
00:02:52,080 --> 00:02:54,720
We waited for you because we need to do
a little job.

60
00:02:54,800 --> 00:02:57,680
They bought a new PVC carpet.
We need to stick it in the bedroom.

61
00:02:58,240 --> 00:03:01,200
PVC? What, that's still a thing?

62
00:03:01,840 --> 00:03:03,360
Of course it's still a thing.

63
00:03:04,200 --> 00:03:07,400
Only Rachel wants it in a wood pattern.

64
00:03:07,480 --> 00:03:09,760
So why not wood?
-Do you know how to install wood?

65
00:03:10,320 --> 00:03:11,920
No.
-Then it's PVC.

66
00:03:12,560 --> 00:03:14,160
Fine.
Forget it, Shai, don’t go there,

67
00:03:14,240 --> 00:03:16,680
I’ve been there, it’s not that fun.
I cried, wanted to go home.

68
00:03:16,840 --> 00:03:18,880
You didn’t find your way. It’s just in the mourning room,

69
00:03:18,960 --> 00:03:23,040
And honestly, he’s right.
PVC is way easier to stick down.

70
00:03:23,120 --> 00:03:25,240
Easy?
-Easy, and I could do it myself,

71
00:03:25,360 --> 00:03:27,600
I just get dizzy from the glue smell.

72
00:03:27,680 --> 00:03:32,120
I once glued linoleum,
which is PVC's cousin.

73
00:03:33,200 --> 00:03:35,120
Linoleum?
-Linoleum.

74
00:03:35,280 --> 00:03:39,480
Well, if you finish on time, you’ll get a treat.
-Come on.

75
00:03:40,600 --> 00:03:43,040
Enough, don’t be hysterical.
-I’m not hysterical. Hysterical...

76
00:03:43,320 --> 00:03:47,920
Listen, is the hamster home alone now?
So go home, without the girls,

77
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:51,040
take care of it and later
find a good excuse for why it disappeared.

78
00:03:51,120 --> 00:03:53,720
Yeah? You think the girls
left the hamster home alone?

79
00:03:53,880 --> 00:03:56,280
It’s out here on your balcony.
-At my place?

80
00:03:56,880 --> 00:03:59,800
What, Mom? Just for hysterics?
-Wait, a hamster is a lovely pet.

81
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:03,280
It’s like Grandpa. Just without the beard.
-Lovely and annoying.

82
00:04:03,840 --> 00:04:07,360
Speaking of annoying, where’s Meirav?
-She went to the synagogue, God forbid.

83
00:04:07,440 --> 00:04:09,160
What now, synagogue? What, is she becoming religious?

84
00:04:09,760 --> 00:04:11,360
Why would she become religious? Did she go off the derech?

85
00:04:11,440 --> 00:04:14,880
Meirav says you don’t go
to synagogue to become religious.

86
00:04:15,080 --> 00:04:18,560
You go to synagogue
to find a match with good lineage.

87
00:04:19,120 --> 00:04:21,680
A match?
-Wait, but even if she finds a match,

88
00:04:21,920 --> 00:04:22,960
he’ll be from a religious family.

89
00:04:23,080 --> 00:04:24,280
So?
-Why would he want her?

90
00:04:24,360 --> 00:04:26,040
So what? Aren’t we traditional?

91
00:04:26,280 --> 00:04:30,760
Mom, we’re traditional in "L." That guy
probably wants someone modest and nice,

92
00:04:31,360 --> 00:04:33,720
someone who hasn’t seen Joseph and his brothers.

93
00:04:34,240 --> 00:04:37,480
Someone who splits hooves,
chews the cud, and is kosher...

94
00:04:37,560 --> 00:04:38,760
So what’s the problem?

95
00:04:41,240 --> 00:04:43,320
We have the glue, the spatula, and the PVC.

96
00:04:43,880 --> 00:04:47,000
Is there enough PVC?
-There’s a meter and a half spare.

97
00:04:47,880 --> 00:04:50,560
No mistakes allowed. Got it?

98
00:04:50,680 --> 00:04:52,840
Don’t worry, you’ll still be able to return
that meter and a half.

99
00:04:52,920 --> 00:04:55,320
Then I’d be very happy.
-So come on, let’s start.

100
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:57,400
Alright, let’s start.

101
00:04:58,040 --> 00:05:00,600
Start! Here, in this corner, please.

102
00:05:00,680 --> 00:05:03,240
Okay, Dad, can you go?
-No, I just want to see

103
00:05:03,360 --> 00:05:04,920
that you know what you’re doing. What’s wrong?

104
00:05:05,040 --> 00:05:07,320
Fine. Go, come back in half an hour,
an hour, everything will be done.

105
00:05:07,800 --> 00:05:10,400
For some reason, suddenly, I’m not relaxed. What now?

106
00:05:10,520 --> 00:05:12,160
Well, you know what, Dad? Let’s make a bet

107
00:05:12,240 --> 00:05:14,640
that we finish this job
here perfectly without a single flaw.

108
00:05:14,720 --> 00:05:16,840
How?
-You’re going to get a finish

109
00:05:17,080 --> 00:05:19,640
like in a fancy place.
-Alright then...

110
00:05:19,800 --> 00:05:21,800
So start and I’ll be on my way.

111
00:05:22,840 --> 00:05:25,040
Didn’t you say earlier you wanted
to watch the game on TV?

112
00:05:25,120 --> 00:05:28,640
I’m recording it. Now start.

113
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:31,400
Open the glue.
-What? What’s the deal?

114
00:05:32,560 --> 00:05:36,560
Did you know this glue is made from horses?

115
00:05:38,680 --> 00:05:41,080
I’m leaving. Start, start.
-Thanks.

116
00:05:44,800 --> 00:05:47,080
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom.

117
00:05:47,440 --> 00:05:49,760
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom.

118
00:05:51,200 --> 00:05:52,880
Shabbat Shalom, Silvan.

119
00:05:54,400 --> 00:05:56,240
Shabbat Shalom.
-Shabbat Shalom.

120
00:05:56,360 --> 00:05:58,840
What’s this, we’re sitting down?
-No, the women are in the kitchen.

121
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:03,760
Shai and Manny are in the living room.
-What is this? A dance competition for horses?

122
00:06:03,880 --> 00:06:05,960
Yeah.
-I wish I could join a competition like that.

123
00:06:06,040 --> 00:06:07,000
I'm really good at it.

124
00:06:07,080 --> 00:06:10,280
Seriously, you're good at dancing?
-No, I'm good with animals.

125
00:06:10,360 --> 00:06:13,920
Dad, can we stop with this?
What are Shai and Manny doing in the living room?

126
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:17,640
They're sticking PVC to the floor.
-And why didn't you wait for Moshe?

127
00:06:18,520 --> 00:06:25,000
Moshe? We don't need him. Just an extra hand.
It's a job... a complex job, complex.

128
00:06:25,080 --> 00:06:27,960
So what? Just so you know, Moshe
can do complex tasks too.

129
00:06:28,080 --> 00:06:29,160
It would take them half the time.

130
00:06:29,240 --> 00:06:31,160
Orna...
-Moshe, be quiet.

131
00:06:31,920 --> 00:06:35,080
Moshe, you're not mad at me, right?

132
00:06:35,480 --> 00:06:38,880
What can I say?
I think it's a complex job and you...

133
00:06:38,960 --> 00:06:41,200
It just doesn't add up for me.

134
00:06:41,960 --> 00:06:43,720
Correct me if I'm wrong.
-You're right.

135
00:06:43,800 --> 00:06:45,200
Please.
-Or wrong.

136
00:06:46,120 --> 00:06:49,440
What was the question?
-Okay. I'm tired of your attitude towards Moshe.

137
00:06:49,560 --> 00:06:51,800
Fine, ugh...
-Wait. Do you want to go?

138
00:06:51,880 --> 00:06:53,120
Go help them.
-No need.

139
00:06:53,200 --> 00:06:54,200
Go help them.

140
00:06:54,280 --> 00:06:57,280
Exactly, just like her mom, always insulting.

141
00:06:58,080 --> 00:07:00,440
Insult and humiliation.
-Shabbat Shalom.

142
00:07:00,560 --> 00:07:02,520
Shabbat Shalom.
-What, are you in a fighting mood too?

143
00:07:02,600 --> 00:07:08,360
What, did Moshe buy you a hamster?
-What? No, he... Dad...

144
00:07:08,920 --> 00:07:11,480
They won't even let Moshe stick
the PVC with them in the living room.

145
00:07:11,680 --> 00:07:15,400
Maybe he's sensitive to the glue smell?
-No, but both he and I

146
00:07:15,560 --> 00:07:18,760
are sensitive to everyone's disrespect
for Moshe's ability to help.

147
00:07:18,920 --> 00:07:21,640
Enough, why does he need this? It's nonsense.

148
00:07:22,400 --> 00:07:24,760
He shouldn't have to try hard.
-Orna, let's admit that Moshe is...

149
00:07:24,840 --> 00:07:26,480
He's not the handyman of this family.

150
00:07:26,600 --> 00:07:30,440
He's also not the Einstein of the family
or the Louis Pasteur of the family,

151
00:07:30,520 --> 00:07:34,120
but that's his charm, that's what makes him special,

152
00:07:34,680 --> 00:07:37,560
and that's why we love him so much.
So what, do you want to take that away from him?

153
00:07:37,640 --> 00:07:39,440
No, I don't want to take that away from him,

154
00:07:39,560 --> 00:07:42,400
but you've all turned him into
the family fool, and I can't accept that.

155
00:07:42,480 --> 00:07:45,760
No, honey, we didn't turn him.
He came prepared from home.

156
00:07:48,640 --> 00:07:51,520
Spread it evenly. Okay? No lumps.
-Okay.

157
00:07:52,080 --> 00:07:56,240
Hey, Shabbat Shalom. What's up?
-Fine, sticking PVC.

158
00:07:56,800 --> 00:07:59,000
Need help?
-Can't you help him from the living room?

159
00:07:59,080 --> 00:08:02,800
What, do we need to stick it in the living room too?
-No, just the best help

160
00:08:02,880 --> 00:08:04,680
you can give, Moshe, is, you know...

161
00:08:05,120 --> 00:08:06,960
Not to interrupt.
-I know.

162
00:08:07,280 --> 00:08:08,640
But Orna is forcing me. What can I do?

163
00:08:09,240 --> 00:08:11,640
You don't have to.
-How "don't have to"? What choice do I have?

164
00:08:12,040 --> 00:08:15,160
You all know I'm not good at this stuff.
-Come on, Moshe, it's not...

165
00:08:15,280 --> 00:08:19,160
It's not that you're not good at it,
it's... you just aren't successful at it

166
00:08:19,280 --> 00:08:22,520
like you're successful, say, at... at...
-At...

167
00:08:22,840 --> 00:08:24,000
-Exams.

168
00:08:24,080 --> 00:08:25,480
Exactly.
-Exactly.

169
00:08:25,560 --> 00:08:29,120
Okay. What, still, can I mess up
without feeling too much guilt afterward?

170
00:08:29,200 --> 00:08:30,360
Too much guilt?

171
00:08:33,120 --> 00:08:34,919
Baseboards.
-Exactly. Stick the baseboards.

172
00:08:35,559 --> 00:08:36,760
Great.
-Okay?

173
00:08:38,360 --> 00:08:39,200
We need to cut...

174
00:08:39,280 --> 00:08:40,799
Moshe, Moshe!
-Moshe...

175
00:08:40,880 --> 00:08:42,080
No. No.
-What?

176
00:08:42,400 --> 00:08:45,400
No, no, no.
-Thanks, Moshe.

177
00:08:45,480 --> 00:08:47,360
Maybe we should ask Orna to let him off the hook?

178
00:08:47,920 --> 00:08:49,120
Yeah, that would be good.
-You think?

179
00:08:50,600 --> 00:08:53,120
Okay, Moshe, gently. Here are the baseboards.

180
00:08:53,680 --> 00:08:55,920
Start there in the corner. Everything's ready for you.

181
00:08:56,520 --> 00:08:58,360
Here’s the glue.
-Okay.

182
00:09:10,560 --> 00:09:14,920
Moshe, Moshe...
-What? No? No...

183
00:09:16,920 --> 00:09:21,280
Dad! Dad!
-Sweetie, Dad's in the bedroom.

184
00:09:21,840 --> 00:09:25,200
I suggest you don’t go in there,
it smells really strong of glue.

185
00:09:25,280 --> 00:09:27,640
The hamster got away.
-So you don’t need Dad,

186
00:09:27,720 --> 00:09:29,400
you need Mom. She’ll be really happy.

187
00:09:31,400 --> 00:09:33,840
What do you mean "the hamster got away"?
-It ran away.

188
00:09:33,920 --> 00:09:34,840
Didn’t you see where?

189
00:09:34,920 --> 00:09:36,520
No.
-Rachel!

190
00:09:37,520 --> 00:09:39,160
Rachel!
-What happened?

191
00:09:39,240 --> 00:09:42,920
There’s a free mouse roaming around the house.
-What mouse?

192
00:09:43,240 --> 00:09:45,280
A mouse, a mouse... look, she says.
The hamster ran away from them.

193
00:09:45,360 --> 00:09:48,160
Oh, thank God.
-Ah, it’s the hamster. Where did it run off to?

194
00:09:48,240 --> 00:09:50,920
It’s in the house.
-It’s a house, so let’s find it.

195
00:09:51,040 --> 00:09:53,960
It has nowhere to run.
-Yeah, but it could get into some small opening,

196
00:09:54,040 --> 00:09:56,880
it could die there from hunger.

197
00:09:56,960 --> 00:09:59,720
It’ll stink up the whole house. That’s what
I need, a dead hamster in the house.

198
00:09:59,800 --> 00:10:01,560
Even when it’s alive, it’s already pretty stinky.

199
00:10:01,920 --> 00:10:05,400
Shani, it’s your hamster.
Find it and get it out of here!

200
00:10:05,480 --> 00:10:07,760
It’s not mine, Dad, it’s Shai’s.
And when he’s done gluing

201
00:10:07,840 --> 00:10:10,160
the carpet in that room,
he can find it and get rid of it.

202
00:10:10,240 --> 00:10:13,840
Here it is. No, sorry, sorry.
That’s the landlord. Sorry.

203
00:10:14,280 --> 00:10:15,440
Sorry, sorry.
-Oh, that’s the landlord?

204
00:10:15,520 --> 00:10:16,640
Come on. |

205
00:10:16,760 --> 00:10:19,880
Shabbat Shalom, everyone.
-Shabbat Shalom.

206
00:10:19,960 --> 00:10:21,320
Hello, honored rabbi.

207
00:10:21,400 --> 00:10:23,440
Be careful.
-Why? What happened?

208
00:10:23,520 --> 00:10:26,000
Mouse, mouse. It ran away. Here. Mouse.

209
00:10:26,080 --> 00:10:27,840
What mouse and what...
-Hamster.

210
00:10:27,960 --> 00:10:29,440
Hamster?
-Hamster, hamster.

211
00:10:29,560 --> 00:10:31,720
Shai bought a hamster for his daughter,
and now it ran away from the cage.

212
00:10:31,800 --> 00:10:34,520
Great, that’s just what I needed.
They’re messing around with

213
00:10:34,640 --> 00:10:38,280
hunting an unclean animal on Shabbat, God have mercy.
-Amen. Amen.

214
00:10:38,360 --> 00:10:41,400
Maybe instead of Him having mercy, He’ll
help us find that hamster.

215
00:10:41,600 --> 00:10:44,360
Okay, listen up, the whole Hasson family

216
00:10:44,480 --> 00:10:47,040
with all its branches and offshoots,
I don’t care about anything,

217
00:10:47,200 --> 00:10:50,480
no more messing around with any hamsters.
My match is coming soon

218
00:10:50,600 --> 00:10:51,680
from the synagogue. Got it?

219
00:10:51,760 --> 00:10:53,360
Mazal Tov!
-Mazal Tov!

220
00:10:53,480 --> 00:10:55,400
Mazal Tov, Meirav.

221
00:10:59,320 --> 00:11:04,080
I mean, wow? This glue is really strong.

222
00:11:04,160 --> 00:11:06,760
Of course it’s strong, Moshe.
It’s meant for carpets, not your shoes.

223
00:11:06,840 --> 00:11:09,440
Moshe, you’re now stuck to the carpet
or the carpet’s coming up

224
00:11:09,520 --> 00:11:12,040
and we’re losing the bet with Silvan.
-That piece is already a goner anyway.

225
00:11:12,120 --> 00:11:15,840
There goes the meter and a half of spare.
-Wait, wait. I have a brilliant idea.

226
00:11:19,400 --> 00:11:22,720
Ta-da!
-No way, you’re a genius, Moshe.

227
00:11:22,800 --> 00:11:25,880
Here it is!
-Stop! Stop!

228
00:11:26,040 --> 00:11:29,240
That’s my husband. You’ve already killed her. Enough.

229
00:11:29,480 --> 00:11:33,360
Okay, listen to me, please.
I have a date, and this time it’s doubly important

230
00:11:33,560 --> 00:11:37,440
because with the religious, there aren’t too many checks.
One meeting and a wedding.

231
00:11:37,600 --> 00:11:39,320
We have to close this gap.

232
00:11:39,480 --> 00:11:43,840
I know you’d like
me to find a partner and get out of the house

233
00:11:43,960 --> 00:11:45,240
and relax a bit...

234
00:11:45,320 --> 00:11:46,880
What are you talking about?
-What are you talking about?

235
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:49,000
Okay, enough, enough, enough. Alright. Let her speak.

236
00:11:49,080 --> 00:11:50,280
Thanks, Mom.
-You’re welcome.

237
00:11:50,400 --> 00:11:55,520
So what I wanted to ask each of you
is to make a small effort for me, please.

238
00:11:55,840 --> 00:11:57,840
What effort, Meirav?
-Minimal.

239
00:11:58,040 --> 00:12:01,120
Dad, from now on you’ll wear a kippah.
-I’m willing for you

240
00:12:01,240 --> 00:12:04,960
to even grow sidelocks. Just that will take a bit of time.

241
00:12:05,280 --> 00:12:08,800
Dad, this isn’t the time for jokes
and it’s not a place for clowns, I’m sorry.

242
00:12:09,360 --> 00:12:12,080
God help us.
-Girls, you need long skirts.

243
00:12:12,640 --> 00:12:13,880
Long?
-Long.

244
00:12:14,080 --> 00:12:16,600
The longer, the better
it shows you’re more modest.

245
00:12:17,080 --> 00:12:19,760
And of course, the news is that pretty much all of you here,

246
00:12:19,920 --> 00:12:22,640
need head coverings.
-Oh, come on, how long is this going to last,

247
00:12:22,720 --> 00:12:24,480
this head covering?
-Until the wedding is decided.

248
00:12:24,560 --> 00:12:26,560
Do I have to?
-Come on, let her talk.

249
00:12:26,640 --> 00:12:27,520
Thanks, Mom.
-You’re welcome.

250
00:12:27,600 --> 00:12:29,200
From now on...
-Miravi, Miravi,

251
00:12:29,680 --> 00:12:32,720
in the end, he should love you for who you are,

252
00:12:32,800 --> 00:12:34,720
not because of skirts and head coverings.

253
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:36,960
Of course, in the end, he won’t have a choice

254
00:12:37,040 --> 00:12:40,080
and he’ll love you for who you are.

255
00:12:40,160 --> 00:12:42,800
This is really the perfect trap.

256
00:12:42,880 --> 00:12:44,840
A mouse!
-Is that Dad's husband?

257
00:12:45,160 --> 00:12:47,400
Did your husband just go to the kitchen?
-No, she’s here.

258
00:12:47,480 --> 00:12:49,000
Come on, to the kitchen, to the kitchen. Let’s go.

259
00:12:49,680 --> 00:12:53,440
I can’t believe that what’s ruining my chances,
which are already slim,

260
00:12:53,520 --> 00:12:56,920
